data.content:
Three EF Core 10 breaking changes hit your code:

---

## 1. `ExecuteUpdateAsync` — now takes a regular lambda, not an expression tree

Your manual `Expression.Lambda` / `Expression.Call` construction **won't compile**. Replace with a simple lambda:

```csharp
// .NET 10 — no expression tree needed
await context.Blogs.ExecuteUpdateAsync(s =>
{
    s.SetProperty(b => b.Views, 8);
    if (nameChanged)
    {
        s.SetProperty(b => b.Name, "foo");
    }
});
```

---

## 2. Complex type column names — uniquified & full-path nested

Two changes affect your model:

| Scenario | Old column name | New column name |
|----------|----------------|-----------------|
| `ShippingAddress.Street` + `BillingAddress.Street` | `ShippingAddress_Street`, `BillingAddress_Street` | `ShippingAddress_Street1`, `BillingAddress_Street2` (uniquified) |
| `Order.Payment.BillingAddress.City` (nested) | `BillingAddress_City` | `Payment_BillingAddress_City` (full path) |

A generated migration will try to rename these columns. **Fix:** pin the old names explicitly:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Customer>(b => {
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.ShippingAddress, sa =>
        sa.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("ShippingAddress_Street"));
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.BillingAddress, ba =>
        ba.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("BillingAddress_Street"));
});

modelBuilder.Entity<Order>(b => {
    b.ComplexProperty(o => o.Payment, p =>
        p.ComplexProperty(pay => pay.BillingAddress, ba =>
            ba.Property(a => a.City).HasColumnName("BillingAddress_City")));
});
```

---

## 3. `IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger` — new `logCommandText` parameter

Methods like `CommandReaderExecuting` now require an additional `string logCommandText` parameter:

```csharp
public class MyLogger : IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger
{
    public InterceptionResult<DbDataReader> CommandReaderExecuting(
        IRelationalConnection connection,
        DbCommand command,
        DbContext context,
        Guid commandId,
        Guid connectionId,
        DateTimeOffset startTime,
        string logCommandText)   // ← new parameter (redacted SQL)
    {
        // Use logCommandText for safe logging (constants may be redacted)
        // Use command.CommandText for actual SQL
    }
}
```

---

**Summary:** The expression-tree rewrite is the biggest win — it dramatically simplifies your code. The other two are mechanical signature/config changes.
